programming language that runs in web browsers. Built with high 
concurrency applications in mind, Node is well suited for applications 
that require real-time, persistent connections. It is also effective 
when a project benefits from having a unified language across the client
 and server sides.</p>

		<p>Developers at <%= @guest_setting.title %> have worked with Node.js in conjunction with
 Ruby to build applications designed to scale to tens of thousands of 
simultaneous users all being updated in real-time. Whether a project 
needs to update charts with up-to-the-second information or enable mass 
communication between thousands of users, <%= @guest_setting.title %> can put Node.js to 
work.</p>
